It is especially interesting to observe the operations of the sper— matozoa. If a single egg be placed in a humid chamber arranged on an object-glass and a few spermatozoa be admitted at some distance from the egg, a very exciting display takes place under the eyes of the observer. The spermatozoa show a high degree of vivacity and run searching in all directions as if they had a sense of the remote ovum. One has a distinct impression that here there must be either two attrac- tive forces, the egg being the more power-ful, or a conscious activity on the part of the spermatozoa.

With regard to the changes which take place in the impregnated egg, I only refer to the following.
